[
    {
        "content": "<p>does somebody know which strict (i.e. Cat-enriched) weighted (co)limits the categories Ps(K,Cat) and Hom(K,Cat) repectively have? here K is a strict 2 category, or even a 1 category if it helps. I know that there is a 2 monad T on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Cat</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\prod_{ob K} \\operatorname{Cat}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0497em;vertical-align:-0.2997em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1864em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">b</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cat</span></span></span></span></span> such that the two 2 categories are TAlg and PsTAlg repsectively, whih implies that they both have all (PIE)-weighted limits. I have also seen that Hom(K,Cat) has all (flexible)-weighted limits. What about strict colimits though?</p>",
        "id": 364779381,
        "sender_full_name": "Nico Beck",
        "timestamp": 1686301125
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't actually <em>know</em> the following, but I hope it's true:</p>\n<p><strong>Conjecture.</strong>  If V is a Benabou cosmos (a complete and cocomplete closed symmetric monoidal category) and K is a V-category, then Hom(K,V) has all small weighted limits and colimits.</p>",
        "id": 364874186,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1686320825
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If it's true you could take V = Cat and the answer to your last question would be \"yes\".</p>",
        "id": 364874277,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1686320848
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Someone should have studied this since Hom(K,V) is what I'd call an \"enriched presheaf category\" and they're pretty important.</p>",
        "id": 364874503,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1686320902
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think by Hom(K,Cat) Nico means the 2-category of pseudofunctors and pseudonatural transformations.  That may have strict coproducts, but I doubt it has any other strict limits.</p>",
        "id": 364883944,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686322784
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(By the way, Nico, you need two dollar-signs around all math here.)</p>",
        "id": 364884109,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686322809
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay,  I guess I don't know what Nico meant by \"the categories Ps(K,Cat) and Hom(K,Cat), respectively\".</p>",
        "id": 364884933,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1686322974
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wait, if that's Hom(K,Cat), then what is Ps(K,Cat)?</p>",
        "id": 364885178,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1686323033
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Strict 2-functors and pseudonatural transformations.  I didn't immediately know what he meant by either of those notations, but then when he said \"there is a 2 monad T on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\prod_{{\\rm ob} K} \\rm Cat</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0497em;vertical-align:-0.2997em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1864em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">ob</span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cat</span></span></span></span></span> such that the two 2 categories are TAlg and PsTAlg repsectively\" I reached this guess.</p>",
        "id": 364885422,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686323076
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because I know there is such a 2-monad such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mi>s</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T {\\rm Alg}_s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9386em;vertical-align:-0.2441em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.0573em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4559em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">s</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2441em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> (the 2-category of strict <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-algebras and strict <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-morphisms) consists of strict 2-functors and strict 2-natural transformations, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T{\\rm Alg}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span></span></span></span></span> (the 2-category of strict <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-algebras and pseudo <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-morphisms) consists of strict 2-functors and pseudonatural transformations, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\rm Ps}T{\\rm Alg}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Ps</span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span></span></span></span></span> (the 2-category of pseudo <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-algebras and pseudo <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-morphisms) consists of pseudofunctors and pseudonatural transformations.</p>",
        "id": 364885904,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686323167
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And those notations for those 2-categories associated to a 2-monad are fairly standard in 2-monad theory.</p>",
        "id": 364886030,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686323199
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/2.20limits.20in.202-categories.20of.20diagrams/near/364883944\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think by Hom(K,Cat) Nico means the 2-category of pseudofunctors and pseudonatural transformations.  That may have strict coproducts, but I doubt it has any other strict limits.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>yes, exactly. by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Cat</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ps(K,\\operatorname{Cat})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cat</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> I mean the 2-category of strict 2-functors, pseudo natural transformations and modifications, and by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Cat</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Hom(K,\\operatorname{Cat})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ho</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cat</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> I mean the 2-category of pseudo functors, pseudo trnadformations and modifications.</p>",
        "id": 364986941,
        "sender_full_name": "Nico Beck",
        "timestamp": 1686352573
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/2.20limits.20in.202-categories.20of.20diagrams/near/364883944\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think by Hom(K,Cat) Nico means the 2-category of pseudofunctors and pseudonatural transformations.  That may have strict coproducts, but I doubt it has any other strict limits.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The 2–category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ps(K,Cat)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> has all (PIE)-weighted strict limits, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Hom(K,Cat)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ho</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> has all (flexible)-weighted strict limits. this is mentioned in remark 7.4 of \"flexible limits for 2-categories\". in general 2 categories of the shape TAlg for a 2-monad do not have many strict colimits, but I was under the impresion that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Hom(K,Cat)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Ho</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is also the 2 category of pseudo coalgebras for some 2 comonad. but I don't remember where I read this. So I thought maybe Hom(K,Cat) has some strict colimits?</p>",
        "id": 364987914,
        "sender_full_name": "Nico Beck",
        "timestamp": 1686353158
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/2.20limits.20in.202-categories.20of.20diagrams/near/364886030\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And those notations for those 2-categories associated to a 2-monad are fairly standard in 2-monad theory.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>yes. I am following the notation conventions of the papers on 2-limits and 2-monads by Kelly, Power, Street, Lack, et al. Ps(K,Cat) is an in between thing, where the 0-cells are the strict ones, but the 1-cells are pseudo</p>",
        "id": 364988408,
        "sender_full_name": "Nico Beck",
        "timestamp": 1686353468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However, your notations Ps(K,Cat) and Hom(K,Cat) are not very standard, so it's probably a good idea to tell your readers what you mean by them.</p>",
        "id": 365002854,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686361963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And I wouldn't recommend using \"Hom(K,Cat)\" for the 2-category of pseudofunctors in any case; you may find this in some older papers that use Benabou's term \"homomorphism (of bicategories)\" for pseudofunctor, but that's pretty well deprecated by now.</p>",
        "id": 365003099,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686362138
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But you're right that these are also categories of coalgebras for a 2-comonad; I should have remembered that.  I guess that does mean that Ps(K,Cat), at least, has PIE-colimits, since PIE-limits lift to TAlg for any 2-monad T.  I'm less sure about Hom(K,Cat) since I don't know a general theorem about limits lifting to categories of pseudoalgebras for a 2-monad, but probably it's true?</p>",
        "id": 365003453,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686362343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, I think it's good form to mention and link when you cross-post a question on multiple forums (<a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/q/448467/49\">https://mathoverflow.net/q/448467/49</a>).</p>",
        "id": 365004296,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1686362900
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I am not sure about the flexible colimits. (And I am also not sure about the PIE-colimits because I do not understand most of it well enough at the moment). The result about PIE-limits looks like it works for any 2 monad and thus should also work for comonads and colimits, but the flexible limits seem to depend on replacing the 2 monad T by its flexible replacement T' in the category of finitary monads, and I am not sure that that also works for the comonads, because I do not understand all the finiteness conditions well enough.  I thought maybe someone knows which strict colimits exist and how they are formed. maybe there is even a simpler argument for categories of diagrams, and maybe one can show  that they are formed pointwise and are created by the 2functor into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Cat</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\prod_{obK} \\operatorname{Cat}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0497em;vertical-align:-0.2997em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1864em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">b</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cat</span></span></span></span></span>. That would be really cool. I remember that I have read the statement that at least the bi(co)limits are pointwise formed in the PhD thesis \"Categorical Properties od Differentiable and Topological Stacks\", but it did not contain a proof.  An equivalent question would be what kind of strict 2-(co)limits Fib(B) has, where B is some base category. I believe this notation is standard.</p>",
        "id": 365021805,
        "sender_full_name": "Nico Beck",
        "timestamp": 1686374986
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/2.20limits.20in.202-categories.20of.20diagrams/near/365004296\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>By the way, I think it's good form to mention and link when you cross-post a question on multiple forums (<a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/q/448467/49\">https://mathoverflow.net/q/448467/49</a>).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I am sry about the cross posting! I normally don't do that, but I learned about the zulip server here only yesterday after I already already posted my question on mathoverflow. Since I spend a lot of time last week trying to understand the 2-colimits, I thought I'll try my luck again :)</p>",
        "id": 365022302,
